\n|2\n|He reaches [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]'s [[ashram]] with his army after a war. After getting exceptional hospitality in the ashram, he came to know about the divine cow Nandini. When a famine struck his kingdom he asks his counsel to get Nandini cow from [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]], which the later refuses.\n|-\n|3\n|Angry King Vishwarath reaches the ashram and tries to get the cow forcefully but failed. The humiliated king decides to gain divine power by doing [[Tapas (Indian religions)|tapasya]] and abdicates the throne for his son.\n|-\n|4\n|Vishwarath got the boon of various divine weapons from [[Brahma|Lord Brahma]]. He again reaches [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]'s [[ashram]] to capture Nandini but fails. He vows to gain more power by doing great penance to become a [[Brahmarshi|Brahmarishi]].\n|-\n|5\n|Ayodhya King Sathyavrata anoints his son Harishchandra as the new King and decides to ascend heaven with his mortal body. However, his unnatural wishes got refuted by [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]. He tried to lure [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]]'s son Satya to help him achieve his desires. An angry Satya curses Sathyavrata and makes him [[Trishanku]].\n|-\n|6\n|Vishwarath after severe penance and tapasya gained more powers and blessing of Mother Gayatri, Vishwarath the warrior became Vishwamitra the sage.\n|-\n|7\n|A dejected [[Trishanku]] approaches Vishwamitra to achieve his desires. After knowing that [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]] refused his wishes, Vishwamitra promises him the impossible. But his [[yajna]] got rejected by Indra and other gods.\n|-\n|8\n|Vishwamitra begins creating alternate heaven for Trishanku when gods dismiss him from Indra's heaven.\n|-\n|9\n|[[B\u1e5bhaspati]] (along with [[Narada]] ) tries to persuade Vishwamitra to abandon creation new heaven for Trishanku which he agrees. However, Narada later instigates him reminding the promise he made to Trishanku. Vishwamitra begins more penance to gain uninterrupted access to heaven. Knowing this Indra and other gods (on the advice of Brhaspati) decide to disrupt his [[tapasya]]. They create a celestial Mahashakti after uniting their powers. But he failed and Vishwamitra killed him with his divine powers.\n|-\n|10\n|[[Indra]] decides to disrupt Vishwamitra's penance by sending [[apsara]] Rambha to seduce him. But an angry Vishwamitra curses her and turned her into a rock. She regretted her actions and asked for forgiveness. He gave her the boon that in future she will be liberated by a Maharishi. After failing repeatedly, Indra decides to disrupt his tapasya himself and went to Vishwamitra disguising as a hungry brahmin. But Vishwamitra recognized him easily and still gave his divine food gained from penance. He embarrasses Indra for his malevolent deeds. A dejected and humiliated Indra leaves for heaven.\n|-\n|11\n|Upon advice of Brhaspati, Indra summons apsara [[Menaka|Meneka]] to seduce Vishwamitra. A reluctant Menaka agrees for the task. She decides to take help from [[Rati]] and [[Kamadeva|Kamadev]].\n|-\n|12\n|After severe attempts Menaka successfully gained the attention of Vishwamitra and made him fell in love with her. \n|-\n|13\n|Both of them got married and thus Indra task finally got fulfilled. He then asks Menaka to return back to heaven but Menaka refuses as she's in love with Vishwamitra too. Indra orders her to return as it'll be unnatural for a celestial being to spend time on earth. A year later Menaka gave birth to a daughter. Narada reminds Indra that Menaka hasn't returned to heaven. \n|-\n|14\n|Menaka finally confesses to Vishwamitra that she was sent on a mission by Indra and now as her task is complete she had to return. An angry and disheartened Vishwamitra abandons Menaka and his daughter and sets out to fulfill his vow to become a Maharishi. Menaka also ascended to heaven leaving their daughter behind. [[Rishi]] [[Kanva]] and his wife Gautami found the girl in the forest and adopted her. As a baby, she was surrounded by Shakunta birds ([[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]]: \u0936\u0915\u0941\u0928\u094d\u0924, \u015bakunta). Therefore, he named her Shakuntala (Sanskrit: \u0936\u0915\u0941\u0928\u094d\u0924\u0932\u093e), meaning Shakunta-protected.\n|-\n|15\n|King [[Dushyanta]] arrives in Rishi Kanva's ashram and fell in love with Shakuntala.\n|-\n|16\n|Shakuntala and Dushyant's love blossoms.\n|-\n|17\n|Dushyant proposes Shakuntala for marriage and they have a [[gandharva]] marriage. Having to leave after some time, Dushyant gives Shakuntala a royal ring as a sign of their love, promising her that he will come to her. One day, sage [[Durvasa]] visits the hermitage, but Shakuntala, who is too absorbed in her love for Dushyant, forgets to serve him food. In a fit of anger, sage Durvasa curses her, saying that the person she is thinking about will forget her.\n|-\n|18\n|Shocked friends of Shakuntala begs for forgiveness and the sage, after recollecting his calm, assures her that the person will remember her again when she shows some proof of their acquaintance. Her friends decide not to tell her anything about the curse. Shakuntala got pregnant and Rishi Kanva decides to send her to Dushyanta. \n|-\n|19\n|So, Shakuntala sets off to the capital, [[Hastinapur]], to remind Dushyant of their past love. Dushyanta does not recollect Shakuntala and asks for proof but an accident occurs by which a fish consumes the royal ring, leaving Shakuntala with no formidable proof. A disheartened Shakuntala left the capital. Her mother Menaka helped her and took her to a sage's ashram so that she can give birth to the child. A fisherman brought the lost ring back to the King and his memory and love are rekindled.\n|-\n|20\n|Meanwhile, Shakuntala gave birth to [[Bharata (Mahabharata)|Bharata]]. One day King Dushyanta while hunting met Bharata & Shakuntala, and the couple is finally reunited. A meeting is called in heaven by Indra with combine participation of representatives of earth and heaven. All [[Brahmarshi|Brahmarishis]] are invited and [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]] urges Indra to call Maharishi Vishwamitra too as he'll be soon a Brahamrishi. Narada is asked to invite Vishwamitra which he accepts. During the meeting, a discussion arises about the most valuable matter in the universe. [[Vasishtha|Vashishtha]] concluded that there is nothing more precious than truth. He also named Raja [[Harishchandra]] as the king who follows the difficult path of truth. His claim is challenged by Vishwamitra and he proposes to test Harishchandra's integrity. \n|-\n|21\n|To assess Harishchandra's commitment towards truthfulness, Vishwamitra reaches his court and asks for an unusually huge amount of treasure for yajna purpose which the King readily accepts. Even upon insistence from the King and his counsel, Vishwamitra refuses to take the treasure at once and asks the king to set aside the treasure with himself and he will take it when the right time arrives. Later, Viswamitra creates and send wild animals to Harishchandra's kingdom to further test his mettle. Harishchandra saves his subject from wild animals.\n|-\n|22\n|Using his powers, Vishwamitra creates two Matangi girls and send them to seduce Raja Harishchandra. The girls are not able to seduce Harishchandra. He is rather disgusted with their seductive performance and asked them to leave with some rewards. But the girls refused to take any reward and in turn ask the King to marry them. Harishchandra refuses to marry them as he is already married to Taramati. The girls then offered themselves as concubines which he vehemently refuses. Later a furious Vishwamitra arrives in Harishchandra's court over the rejection of his magical daughters. Even after the strong insistence of Vishwamitra, Harishchandra refuses to marry his daughters and decides to relinquish his kingdom for saving dharma. He hands over his entire kingdom to Vishwamitra but when he prepares to leaves for Kashi with his wife and son, Vishwamitra asks for the money promised to him for yajna purpose. Harishchandra asks for a month's time to fulfill the promise. Vishwamitra sends his disciple Nakshatrik to accompany them.\n|-\n|23\n|On his journey to Kashi, Vishwamitra creates many hurdles to deviate Harishchandra from dharma. He creates Mayamuni to misguide Harishchandra from the correct path. Vishwamitra's disciple Nakshatrik also keeps giving a hard time to Harishchandra throughout his journey. Vishwamitra creates a Betaal to scare Harishchandra and his family at night but Harishchandra kills him in a duel. Finally, they reach Kashi and Nakshatrik asks for the promised money. Unable to pay anything, Harishchandra asks for some time but Nakshatrik gives him the choice to back-out from his words as there is no way he can deliver his commitment. Taramati asks his husband to sell her off as a slave so that he can pay the money to Vishwamitra. A reluctant Harishchandra agrees for it.\n|-\n|24\n|A rich brahmin buys Taramati & her son (named Rohita) and gave the asked money to Nakshatrik. But Vishwamitra refuses the money and gives it to Nakshatrik as his wages. Vishwamitra asks his disciple to rigorously test Harishchandra's commitment to dharma. Nakshatrik goes to Harishchandra and asks for his guru's debt. A shocked Harishchandra decides this time to sell himself.\n|-\n|25\n|A rich drunkard ''chandala'' named Veerbahu buys Harishchandra and renames him Veerdas. He deploys him as dom (untouchable) to perform last rites rituals at Ganga Ghat. Veerbahu instructs him to charge a gold coin, a new cloth, and rice for anyone coming for the last rites ritual. While Harishchandra is busy working as a dom, his wife and son face a lot of hardship at their master's place.\n|-\n|26\n|Taramati's master send Rohita to forest along with others for daily chores. Vishwamitra send Nagraj as snake to kill Rohita. He dies in the forest due to snake-bite and his corpse is later discovered by Taramati. Heart-broken Taramati takes the corpse of his son for cremation where she's stopped by none other than his own husband Harishchandra. They are not able to recognize each other initially. As per his master's instruction he can't let anyone do the last rites with the pre-requisite items. Taramati identifies his husband. A mournful Harishchandra still sticks to his dharma and tells his wife to get the items for cremation. Taramati asks her husband to guard their son's corpse while she gets the items from her master.\n|-\n|27\n|\n|}\n\n== Music ==\nLyrics for various songs were written by Bhring Tupkari and music was composed by Vasu Rao. The title song was performed by [[K. J. Yesudas|Yesudas]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dla.library.upenn.edu/dla/vcat/record.html?id=VCAT_3761598&rotation=0&detail=staff|title=Vishwamitra (1995)|website=dla.library.upenn.edu|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n<br />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0262876}}\n\n\n[[Category:Indian mythological television series]]\n[[Category:1995 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Doordarshan television series]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television programs]]\n", "name_user": "Unclewalker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisodes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vishwamitra_(1995_TV_Series)"}
{"title_page": "K. Raghupati Bhat", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Indian politician\n| name                = K. Raghupathi Bhat\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office              = Member of the [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] for Udupi\n| term_start          = May 2018\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = \n| successor           = [[Pramod Madhwaraj]]\n| term1               = 2004 \u2013 8 May 2013\n| predecessor1        = [[Pramod Madhwaraj]]\n| successor1          = \n| party               = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1969|2|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = Karmballi Udupi\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n}}\n\n'''K. Raghupati Bhat''' (born 24 February 1969)<ref>{{cite news |title=Udupi: Second innings - Raghupati Bhat to marry on Oct 9 |url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=193621 |accessdate=15 June 2018 |work=daijiworld.com}}</ref> is an Indian politician and a member of the [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] representing the constituency of Udupi.<ref>{{cite news |title=BJP makes a clean sweep in Udupi district |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/bjp-makes-a-clean-sweep-in-udupi-district/article23898562.ece |accessdate=15 June 2018 |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2018 |language=en-IN}}</ref> After [[delimitation]] exercise carried out in the year 2008  by Election commission of India,<ref>[http://www.manipalworldnews.com/2014/04/10/udupi-raghupathi-bhat-aggressive-election-campaign-shobha-karandlage-urges-everyone-vote/   Raghupathi bhat does aggressive election campaign for Shobha Karandlage, Urges everyone to Vote] from [[\u201cManipal world news\u201d]]</ref> The Udupi assembly constituency number has changed to 120. He was member of Thirteenth [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] from 30 May 2008 to 5 May 2013  representing Udupi constituency.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kla.kar.nic.in/assembly/member/members.htm|title=Thirteenth Karnataka Legislative Assembly (\u0cb9\u0ca6\u0cbf\u0cae\u0cc2\u0cb0\u0ca8\u0cc7 \u0c95\u0cb0\u0ccd\u0ca8\u0cbe\u0c9f\u0c95 \u0cb5\u0cbf\u0ca7\u0cbe\u0ca8 \u0cb8\u0cad\u0cc6)|date=2019|work=Karnataka Legislative Assembly|access-date=30 September 2019|language=en-IN}}</ref>   He is now member of Fifteenth Karnataka Legislative Assembly (M.L.A) from Udupi.He belongs to [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP). He started as a member of BJP. He was elected to Udupi municipal council and he was also the president of district BJP Yuva morcha (Youth wing).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120103092858/http://raghupathibhat.com/ K Raghupathi Bhat, Official Webpage]\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2007/01/09/stories/2007010916170300.htm  K.Raghupathi Bhat]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhat, K. Raghupati}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Udupi]]\n[[Category:Mangaloreans]]\n[[Category:Tulu people]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Members of the Karnataka Legislative Assembly]]\n\n\n{{BJP-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Indian politician\n| name         = K. Raghupathi Bhat\n| image        =  \n| caption      =\n| office       = Member of the [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] for Udupi\n| term_start   = May 2018\n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  =\n| successor    = [[Pramod Madhwaraj]]\n| term1        = 2004 \u2013 8 May 2013\n| predecessor1 = [[Pramod Madhwaraj]]\n| successor1   = \n| party        = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1969|2|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  =karmballi udupi\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n}}\n\n'''K. Raghupati Bhat''' (born 24 February 1969)<ref>{{cite news |title=Udupi: Second innings - Raghupati Bhat to marry on Oct 9 |url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=193621 |accessdate=15 June 2018 |work=daijiworld.com}}</ref> is an Indian politician and a member of the [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] representing the constituency of Udupi.<ref>{{cite news |title=BJP makes a clean sweep in Udupi district |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/bjp-makes-a-clean-sweep-in-udupi-district/article23898562.ece |accessdate=15 June 2018 |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2018 |language=en-IN}}</ref> After [[delimitation]] exercise carried out in the year 2008  by Election commission of India,<ref>[http://www.manipalworldnews.com/2014/04/10/udupi-raghupathi-bhat-aggressive-election-campaign-shobha-karandlage-urges-everyone-vote/   Raghupathi bhat does aggressive election campaign for Shobha Karandlage, Urges everyone to Vote] from [[\u201cManipal world news\u201d]]</ref> The Udupi assembly constituency number has changed to 120. He was member of Thirteenth [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] from 30 May 2008 to 5 May 2013  representing Udupi constituency.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kla.kar.nic.in/assembly/member/members.htm|title=Thirteenth Karnataka Legislative Assembly (\u0cb9\u0ca6\u0cbf\u0cae\u0cc2\u0cb0\u0ca8\u0cc7 \u0c95\u0cb0\u0ccd\u0ca8\u0cbe\u0c9f\u0c95 \u0cb5\u0cbf\u0ca7\u0cbe\u0ca8 \u0cb8\u0cad\u0cc6)|date=2019|work=Karnataka Legislative Assembly|access-date=30 September 2019|language=en-IN}}</ref>   He is now member of Fifteenth Karnataka Legislative Assembly (M.L.A) from Udupi.He belongs to [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP). He started as a member of BJP. He was elected to Udupi municipal council and he was also the president of district BJP Yuva morcha (Youth wing).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120103092858/http://raghupathibhat.com/ K Raghupathi Bhat, Official Webpage]\n*[http://www.hindu.com/2007/01/09/stories/2007010916170300.htm  K.Raghupathi Bhat]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhat, K. Raghupati}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Udupi]]\n[[Category:Mangaloreans]]\n[[Category:Tulu people]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Members of the Karnataka Legislative Assembly]]\n\n\n{{BJP-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CharlestonMaani", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K._Raghupati_Bhat"}
{"title_page": "Iain Glen", "text_new": "{{Short description|Scottish actor}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Iain Glen\n| image           = Iain_Glen.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = Glen in July 2012\n| birth_name      =\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1961|06|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland\n| years_active    = 1986\u2013present\n| spouse          = {{marriage|[[Susannah Harker]]|1993|2004|end=div}}\n| partner         = Charlotte Emmerson (2005\u2013present)\n| children        = 3\n| occupation      = Actor\n| nationality     =\n| education       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Edinburgh Academy]]\n*[[University of Aberdeen]]\n*[[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]}}\n}}\n'''Iain Glen''' (born 24 June 1961) is a Scottish actor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Murphy |first=Mekado |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/27225/Iain-Glen |title=The New York Times |publisher=Movies.nytimes.com |date=27 December 2016 |accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> Glen is best known for his roles as Dr. Alexander Isaacs/[[Tyrant (Resident Evil)|Tyrant]] in three films of the [[Resident Evil (film series)|''Resident Evil'' film series]] (2004\u20132016) and as [[Jorah Mormont|Ser Jorah Mormont]] in the [[HBO]] fantasy television series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' (2011\u20132019). Other notable roles include [[John Hanning Speke]] in ''[[Mountains of the Moon (film)|Mountains of the Moon]]'', Sir Richard Carlisle in ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', the title role in ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'', and Jarrod Slade in ''[[Cleverman]]''. He currently plays [[Batman|Bruce Wayne]] in the [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]] series ''[[Titans (2018 TV series)|Titans]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nIain Glen was born in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland in 1961, and educated at the [[Edinburgh Academy]], an independent school for boys (now co-educational), followed by the [[University of Aberdeen]]. He then trained in acting at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art|RADA]] in London (\"because it was the only one that was holding auditions at that particular time\"),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Mark |title=Out, out damned spotlight |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1993-04-23/14/ |publisher=The List |accessdate=30 October 2019 |date=23 April 1993}}</ref> where he won the Bancroft Gold Medal. His older brother is Hamish Glen, artistic director of the [[Belgrade Theatre]], [[Coventry]] and former artistic director of the [[Dundee Repertory Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web |title=10 years at the top for our Artistic Director, Hamish Glen |url=http://www.belgrade.co.uk/news-and-blogs/news-list/10-years-at-the-top-for-belgrades-artistic-directo/ |website=Belgrade Theatre Coventry |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2016}}\nIn 1990, Glen won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actor]] at the [[40th Berlin International Film Festival]] for his role in ''[[Silent Scream (1990 film)|Silent Scream]]''. In the same year he was cast as [[Prince Hamlet|Hamlet]], Prince of Denmark in [[Tom Stoppard]]'s [[Rosencrantz & Guildenstern Are Dead (film)|film adaptation]] of his play ''[[Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead]]'', which won the Golden Lion at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1990/03_preistr_ger_1990/03_Preistraeger_1990.html |title=Berlinale: 1990 Prize Winners |accessdate=20 March 2011 |work=Berlinale.de}}</ref>\nHe was nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for his performance in ''[[The Blue Room (play)|The Blue Room]]'' opposite [[Nicole Kidman]].\n\nin 2002, Glen starred with [[Emilia Fox]] in the Italian-French-British romance-drama film [[The Soul Keeper]] directed by [[Roberto Faenza]].\n \nIt was announced in 2009 that Glen would star as [[Jorah Mormont|Ser Jorah Mormont]] in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]''. In 2010, he played the role of Father Octavian, leader of a sect of clerics who were on a mission against the [[Weeping Angel]]s in \"[[The Time of Angels]]\" and \"[[Flesh and Stone]]\", a two-episode story which formed part of the fifth season of the revived television series ''[[Doctor Who]]''.  He appeared in the second series of ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', as Sir Richard Carlisle, a tabloid publisher who is a suitor to, and subsequently engaged to, Lady Mary.\n\nFrom 2010 to the present Glen has played the title character in the Irish TV crime series ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'' adapted from the novels by [[Ken Bruen]].\n\nIn the 2012 BBC drama series ''[[Prisoners' Wives]]'', he plays Paul, the husband of Francesca, whose comfortable life comes crashing down when he is imprisoned for drug trafficking. Also in 2012, he starred in a new 4-part [[BBC Radio 4]] adaptation of ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]'', written by [[Sebastian Baczkiewicz]], directed by [[Jeremy Mortimer]] and Sasha Yevtushenko. In 2013, he played the lead in the new play ''[[Longing (play)|Longing]]''.\n\nFrom 6 December 2013 until early January 2014 Glen starred alongside [[Richard McCabe]] in ''[[Fortune's Fool]]'' at [[the Old Vic]], directed by [[Lucy Bailey]]. He had been due to appear in the full run until 22 February 2014<ref name=oldvic>[http://www.oldvictheatre.com/fortunes-fool/ ''Fortune's Fool''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009035220/http://www.oldvictheatre.com/fortunes-fool |date=9 October 2013 }} at oldvictheatre.com</ref> but was forced to withdraw early to recover from illness, with his role taken by his understudy [[Patrick Cremin]] and then by [[William Houston (actor)|William Houston]] who joined the cast about the same time as Glen's departure.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/game-of-thrones-star-iain-glen-quits-play-with-mystery-illness-9048803.html| title= Game of Thrones star Iain Glen quits play with mystery illness| date=9 January 2014| work= Evening Standard| accessdate= 3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Glen provided the voiceover for a [[Vauxhall Mokka]] advertisement.\n\nIn 2019, it was revealed that Glen would be portraying [[Batman|Bruce Wayne]] on the [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]] TV show ''[[Titans (2018 TV series)|Titans]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/batman-game-of-thrones-star-will-portray-bruce-wayne-on-titans-dc-universe-1202593583/|title=\u2018Game Of Thrones\u2019 Star Will Portray Bruce Wayne On \u2018Titans\u2019|first1=Geoff|last1=Boucher|first2=Geoff|last2=Boucher|date=11 April 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Ian glen.JPG|thumb|upright|Iain Glen as [[Jorah Mormont|Ser Jorah Mormont]] on the set of ''Game of Thrones'']]\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1988\n| [[Paris by Night (film)|''Paris by Night'']]\n| Wallace Sharp\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Gorillas in the Mist]]''\n| Brendan\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4|1990\n| [[Mountains of the Moon (film)|''Mountains of the Moon'']]\n| [[John Hanning Speke]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Silent Scream (1990 film)|''Silent Scream'']]\n| Larry Winters\n| \n|-\n| [[Rosencrantz & Guildenstern Are Dead (film)|''Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead'']]\n| [[Prince Hamlet|Hamlet]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fools of Fortune]]''\n| William Quinton\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''30 Door Key''\n| Joey\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| [[The Young Americans (film)|''The Young Americans'']]\n| Edward Foster\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Marar\u00eda]]''\n| Bertrand\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2000\n| ''[[Beautiful Creatures (2000 film)|Beautiful Creatures]]''\n| Tony\n|\n|-\n| [[Paranoid (2000 thriller film)|''Paranoid'']]\n| Stan\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2001\n| ''[[Lara Croft: Tomb Raider]]''\n| Manfred Powell\n| \n|-\n| [[Gabriel and Me|''Gabriel & Me'']]\n| Dad\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2002\n| [[Darkness (2002 film)|''Darkness'']]\n| Mark\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Soul Keeper]]''\n| [[Carl Gustav Jung|Dr. Carl Gustav Jung]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2003\n| ''[[Song for a Raggy Boy]]''\n| Brother John\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Spy Sorge]]''\n| [[Richard Sorge]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Resident Evil: Apocalypse]]''\n| Dr. Alexander Isaacs\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2005\n| [[Man to Man (2005 film)|''Man to Man'']]\n| Alexander Auchinleck\n|\n|-\n| ''Vagabond Shoes''\n| Alec Murray\n| Short film\n|-\n| [[Tara Road (film)|''Tara Road'']]\n| Danny\n|\n|-\n| [[Kingdom of Heaven (film)|''Kingdom of Heaven'']]\n| [[Richard I of England|Richard C\u0153ur de Lion]]\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Small Engine Repair''\n| Doug\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2007\n| ''[[The Last Legion]]''\n| [[Orestes (father of Romulus Augustulus)|Orestes]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Resident Evil: Extinction]]''\n| Dr. Alexander Isaacs / [[Tyrant (Resident Evil)|Tyrant]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mrs Ratcliffe's Revolution]]''\n| Frank Ratcliffe\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Slapper''\n| Red / Michael Simmons\n| Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2009\n| [[Pope Joan (2009 film)|''Pope Joan'']]\n| Village Priest\n|\n|-\n| [[Harry Brown (film)|''Harry Brown'']]\n| S.I. Childs\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Case of Unfaithful Klara (film)|The Case of Unfaithful Klara]]''\n| Denis\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Iron Lady (film)|''The Iron Lady'']]''\n| [[Alfred Roberts]]\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Kick-Ass 2 (film)|Kick-Ass 2]]''\n| Uncle Ralph\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2014\n| ''[[Guy Martin|Guy Martin's Spitfire]]''\n| Narrator (voice)\n| Documentary\n|-\n| ''Monsters Behind the Iron Curtain''\n| Narrator (voice)\n| Documentary\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2015\n| ''[[The Bad Education Movie]]''\n| Pasco\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Eye in the Sky (2015 film)|Eye in the Sky]]''\n| James Willett\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| ''[[Resident Evil: The Final Chapter]]''\n| Dr. Alexander Isaacs\n|\n|-\n| ''Dusty and Me''\n| Mickey the Bubble\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[My Cousin Rachel (2017 film)|My Cousin Rachel]]''\n| Nick Kendall\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Flood (2019 film)|The Flood]]''\n| Philip\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''The Fabric of You ''\n| Isaac (voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Isabel ''\n| Colin\n| Short film, completed\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2020\n| ''[[What About Love (2020 film)|What About Love]]''\n| American Ambassador\n| Post-production\n|-\n| ''[[The Windermere Children]]''\n| {{TableTBA}}\n| Post-production\n|-\n| ''[[Black Beauty (upcoming film)|Black Beauty]]''\n|\n| Filming\n<!--do NOT put films that have not begun filming yet per WP:CRYSTAL-->\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Taggart]]''\n| Scott Adair\n| Episode: \"Knife Edge\"\n|-\n| 1986\u20131989\n| ''[[Screen Two]]''\n|  Allan Innes / Sailor / Ray\n| 3 episodes \n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The Fear (1988 TV series)|The Fear]]''\n| Carl Galton\n| 5 episodes \n|-\n| 1991\n| [[Adam Bede#Film, TV or theatrical adaptations|''Adam Bede'']]\n| [[Adam Bede (character)|Adam Bede]]\n| [[Television film]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1992\n| ''[[Frankie's House (TV miniseries)|Frankie's House]]''\n| [[Tim Page (photographer)|Tim Page]]\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Screen One]]''\n| Cmdr Powell\n| Episode: \"Black and Blue\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Missus''\n| Father Pietro Salviati, Missus\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Death of a Salesman (1996 film)|Death of a Salesman]]''\n| Biff\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1997\n| [[Painted Lady (mini series)|''Painted Lady'']]\n| Sebastian Stafford\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1998\n| [[Trial and Retribution|''Trial & Retribution'']]\n| Damon Morton\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1999\n| [[Wives and Daughters (1999 miniseries)|''Wives and Daughters'']]\n| Mr. Preston\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2000\n| ''Glasgow Kiss''\n| Stuart Morrison\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[The Wyvern Mystery]]''\n| Charles Fairfield\n| Television film\n|-\n| ''Anchor Me''\n| Nathan Carter\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''Impact''\n| Marcus Hodge\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Carla''\n| Daniel\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[Kidnapped (2005 miniseries)|''Kidnapped'']]\n| [[Alan Breck]]\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2007\n| ''[[Starting Over (2007 film)|Starting Over]]''\n| Gregor Dewhurst\n| Television film\n|-\n| ''[[The Relief of Belsen]]''\n| [[James Johnston (British Army medical officer)|James Johnston]]\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[City of Vice]]''\n| [[John Fielding]]\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2009\n| ''[[The Diary of Anne Frank (2009 miniseries)|The Diary of Anne Frank]]''\n| [[Otto Frank]]\n| 5 episodes\n|- \n| [[Law and Order: UK|''Law & Order: UK'']]\n| Luke Slade\n| Episode: \"Unsafe\"\n|-\n| ''[[Into the Storm (2009 film)|Into the Storm]]''\n| [[George VI of the United Kingdom|King George VI]]\n| Television film\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2010\n| ''[[Doctor Who]]''\n| Father Octavian\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''\n| Vaughn Edwards\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2010\u20132016\n| ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]''\n| Jack Taylor\n| Series of television films\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2011\n| ''[[Strike Back: Project Dawn]]''\n| Crawford\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Downton Abbey]]''\n| [[List of Downton Abbey characters#Sir Richard Carlisle|Sir Richard Carlisle]]\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2011\u20132019\n| ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\n| [[Jorah Mormont|Ser Jorah Mormont]]\n| Main role\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2012\n| ''[[Haven (TV series)|Haven]]''\n| Roland Holloway\n| Episode: \"Real Estate\"\n|-\n| ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Part II]]''\n| [[Richard de Beauchamp, 13th Earl of Warwick|Earl of Warwick]]\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''[[Prisoners' Wives]]\n| Paul\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2013\n| ''[[Borgia (TV series)|Borgia]]''\n| [[Girolamo Savonarola]]\n| 2 episodes \n|-\n| ''[[Ripper Street]]''\n| Colonel Madoc Faulkner\n| Episode: \"The Weight of One Man's Heart\"\n|-\n| ''[[Agatha Christie's Poirot]]''\n| Dr. David Willoughby\n| Episode: \"Elephants Can Remember\"\n|-\n| ''[[Breathless (TV series)|Breathless]]''\n| Inspector Ronald Mulligan\n| 6 episodes\n|- \n| 2014\u20132017\n| ''[[Autopsy: The Last Hours of...|Autopsy: The Last Hours Of]]''\n| Narrator (voice)\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Red Tent (miniseries)|The Red Tent]]''\n| [[Jacob]]\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Cleverman]]''\n| Jarrod Slade\n| 12 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132019\n| ''[[Delicious (TV series)|Delicious]]''\n| Leo\n| 12 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2018\n| ''[[The Sidemen Show]]''\n| Narrator (voice)\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Mrs Wilson]]''\n| [[Alexander Wilson (British writer)|Alexander \"Alec\" Wilson]]\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2019\n| ''Ice Age: Return of the Mammoth''\n| Narrator (voice)\n| Television documentary\n|-\n| ''[[Titans (2018 TV series)|Titans]]''\n| [[Batman|Bruce Wayne]]\n| 5 episodes\n|}\n\n==Selected theatre==\n*''[[Edward II (play)|Edward II]]'', [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]] 1986\n*''[[The Man Who Had All the Luck]]'' [[Bristol Old Vic]] 1990\n*''[[Hamlet]]'', [[Bristol Old Vic]], 1991\n*''[[Macbeth]]'' (1993) \n*''[[Henry V (play)|Henry V]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Martin Guerre (musical)|Martin Guerre]]'' (1996\u20131997) \n*''[[The Blue Room (play)|The Blue Room]]'' (1998) \n*''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' (2002)\n*''[[Hedda Gabler]]'' (2005)\n*''[[The Crucible]]'' (2006)\n*''Scenes of a Marriage'' (2008)\n*''[[Wallenstein (play)|Wallenstein]]'' (2009, [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester]]) \u2013 title role\n*''[[Separate Tables]]'' (2009) \u2013 roles of Mr Martin and Major Pollock \u2013 [[Chichester Festival Theatre]]\n*''[[Ghosts (play)|Ghosts]]'' (2010) \u2013 also directed\n*''[[Uncle Vanya]]'', The Print Room, 2012 \u2013 title role\n*''[[Fortune's Fool]]'', [[The Old Vic]], 2013<ref name=\"oldvictheatre.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldvictheatre.com/fortunes-fool/ |title=Fortune\u2019s Fool |publisher=Oldvictheatre.com |date=4 October 2013 |access-date=11 February 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009035220/http://www.oldvictheatre.com/fortunes-fool |archive-date=9 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*''[[The Seagull]]''\n*''[[Here (play)|Here]]''\n*''[[King Lear]]''\n*''[[Coriolanus (play)|Coriolanus]]''\n*''[[She Stoops to Conquer]]''\n*''[[Hapgood (play)|Hapgood]]''\n*''[[Road (play)|Road]]''\n*''Small Engine Repair''\n*''[[The Recruiting Officer]]''\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n|-\n|1990\n|[[Silver Bear]]\n|[[Silver Bear for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n|''[[Silent Scream (1990 film)|Silent Scream]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1991\n|[[Evening Standard British Film Award]]\n|Best Actor\n|''[[Mountains of the Moon (film)|Mountains of the Moon]]'', ''[[Fools of Fortune]]'', ''[[Silent Scream (1990 film)|Silent Scream]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Ian Charleson Award]]\n|Special commendation<ref>Lees, Caroline. \"Classic recipes for success\". ''Sunday Times''. 9 February 1992</ref>\n|''[[Hamlet]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|1994\n|[[Evening Standard Theatre Award]]\n|Best Actor\n|''[[Henry V (play)|Henry V]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1997\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award]]\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]\n|''[[Martin Guerre (musical)|Martin Guerre]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1999\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award]]\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n|''[[The Blue Room (play)|The Blue Room]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Drama League Award]]\n|Best Actor\n|''The Blue Room''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2007\n|[[Whatsonstage.com Awards|Whatsonstage.com Award]]\n|Best Actor\n|''[[The Crucible]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award]]\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n|''The Crucible''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|{{nowrap|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]]}}\n|''[[Game of Thrones]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2013\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Game of Thrones''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|''[[Downton Abbey]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2014\n|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Game of Thrones''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2015\n|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Game of Thrones''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Game of Thrones''\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.iainglen.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|322513|Iain Glen}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n\n{{navboxes\n|title=Awards for Iain Glen\n|list1=\n{{EquityAward TVDramaCast}}\n{{Silver Bear for Best Actor}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glen, Iain}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n[[Category:Scottish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male television actors]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:British male television actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:People educated at Edinburgh Academy]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Scottish actor}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Iain Glen\n| image           = Iain_Glen.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = Glen in July 2012\n| birth_name      =\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1961|06|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland\n| years_active    = 1986\u2013present\n| spouse          = {{marriage|[[Susannah Harker]]|1993|2004|end=div}}\n| partner         = Charlotte Emmerson (2005\u2013present)\n| children        = 3\n| occupation      = Actor\n| nationality     =\n| education       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Edinburgh Academy]]\n*[[University of Aberdeen]]\n*[[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]}}\n}}\n'''Iain Glen''' (born 24 June 1961) is a Scottish actor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Murphy |first=Mekado |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/27225/Iain-Glen |title=The New York Times |publisher=Movies.nytimes.com |date=27 December 2016 |accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> Glen is best known for his roles as Dr. Alexander Isaacs/[[Tyrant (Resident Evil)|Tyrant]] in three films of the [[Resident Evil (film series)|''Resident Evil'' film series]] (2004\u20132016) and as [[Jorah Mormont|Ser Jorah Mormont]] in the [[HBO]] fantasy television series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' (2011\u20132019). Other notable roles include [[John Hanning Speke]] in ''[[Mountains of the Moon (film)|Mountains of the Moon]]'', Sir Richard Carlisle in ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', the title role in ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'', and Jarrod Slade in ''[[Cleverman]]''. He currently plays [[Batman|Bruce Wayne]] in the [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]] series ''[[Titans (2018 TV series)|Titans]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nIain Glen was born in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland in 1961, and educated at the [[Edinburgh Academy]], an independent school for boys (now co-educational), followed by the [[University of Aberdeen]]. He then trained in acting at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art|RADA]] in London (\"because it was the only one that was holding auditions at that particular time\"),<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Mark |title=Out, out damned spotlight |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1993-04-23/14/ |publisher=The List |accessdate=30 October 2019 |date=23 April 1993}}</ref> where he won the Bancroft Gold Medal. His older brother is Hamish Glen, artistic director of the [[Belgrade Theatre]], [[Coventry]] and former artistic director of the [[Dundee Repertory Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web |title=10 years at the top for our Artistic Director, Hamish Glen |url=http://www.belgrade.co.uk/news-and-blogs/news-list/10-years-at-the-top-for-belgrades-artistic-directo/ |website=Belgrade Theatre Coventry |accessdate=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2016}}\nIn 1990, Glen won the [[Silver Bear for Best Actor]] at the [[40th Berlin International Film Festival]] for his role in ''[[Silent Scream (1990 film)|Silent Scream]]''. In the same year he was cast as [[Prince Hamlet|Hamlet]], Prince of Denmark in [[Tom Stoppard]]'s [[Rosencrantz & Guildenstern Are Dead (film)|film adaptation]] of his play ''[[Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead]]'', which won the Golden Lion at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1990/03_preistr_ger_1990/03_Preistraeger_1990.html |title=Berlinale: 1990 Prize Winners |accessdate=20 March 2011 |work=Berlinale.de}}</ref>\nHe was nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for his performance in ''[[The Blue Room (play)|The Blue Room]]'' opposite [[Nicole Kidman]].\n\nin 2002, Glen starred with [[Emilia Fox]] in the Italian-French-British romance-drama film [[The Soul Keeper]] directed by [[Roberto Faenza]].\n \nIt was announced in 2009 that Glen would star as [[Jorah Mormont|Ser Jorah Mormont]] in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]''. In 2010, he played the role of Father Octavian, leader of a sect of clerics who were on a mission against the [[Weeping Angel]]s in \"[[The Time of Angels]]\" and \"[[Flesh and Stone]]\", a two-episode story which formed part of the fifth season of the revived television series ''[[Doctor Who]]''.  He appeared in the second series of ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', as Sir Richard Carlisle, a tabloid publisher who is a suitor to, and subsequently engaged to, Lady Mary.\n\nFrom 2010 to the present Glen has played the title character in the Irish TV crime series ''[[Jack Taylor (TV series)|Jack Taylor]]'' adapted from the novels by [[Ken Bruen]].\n\nIn the 2012 BBC drama series ''[[Prisoners' Wives]]'', he plays Paul, the husband of Francesca, whose comfortable life comes crashing down when he is imprisoned for drug trafficking. Also in 2012, he starred in a new 4-part [[BBC Radio 4]] adaptation of ''[[The Count of Monte Cristo]]'', written by [[Sebastian Baczkiewicz]], directed by [[Jeremy Mortimer]] and Sasha Yevtushenko. In 2013, he played the lead in the new play ''[[Longing (play)|Longing]]''.\n\nFrom 6 December 2013 until early January 2014 Glen starred alongside [[Richard McCabe]] in ''[[Fortune's Fool]]'' at [[the Old Vic]], directed by [[Lucy Bailey]]. He had been due to appear in the full run until 22 February 2014<ref name=oldvic>[http://www.oldvictheatre.com/fortunes-fool/ ''Fortune's Fool''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009035220/http://www.oldvictheatre.com/fortunes-fool |date=9 October 2013 }} at oldvictheatre.com</ref> but was forced to withdraw early to recover from illness, with his role taken by his understudy [[Patrick Cremin]] and then by [[William Houston (actor)|William Houston]] who joined the cast about the same time as Glen's departure.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/game-of-thrones-star-iain-glen-quits-play-with-mystery-illness-9048803.html| title= Game of Thrones star Iain Glen quits play with mystery illness| date=9 January 2014| work= Evening Standard| accessdate= 3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Glen provided the voiceover for a [[Vauxhall Mokka]] advertisement.\n\nIn 2019, it was revealed that Glen would be portraying [[Batman|Bruce Wayne]] on the [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]] TV show ''[[Titans (2018 TV series)|Titans]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/batman-game-of-thrones-star-will-portray-bruce-wayne-on-titans-dc-universe-1202593583/|title=\u2018Game Of Thrones\u2019 Star Will Portray Bruce Wayne On \u2018Titans\u2019|first1=Geoff|last1=Boucher|first2=Geoff|last2=Boucher|date=11 April 2019|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Ian glen.JPG|thumb|upright|Iain Glen as [[Jorah Mormont|Ser Jorah Mormont]] on the set of ''Game of Thrones'']]\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1988\n| [[Paris by Night (film)|''Paris by Night'']]\n| Wallace Sharp\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Gorillas in the Mist]]''\n| Brendan\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4|1990\n| [[Mountains of the Moon (film)|''Mountains of the Moon'']]\n| [[John Hanning Speke]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Silent Scream (1990 film)|''Silent Scream'']]\n| Larry Winters\n| \n|-\n| [[Rosencrantz & Guildenstern Are Dead (film)|''Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead'']]\n| [[Prince Hamlet|Hamlet]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fools of Fortune]]''\n| William Quinton\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''30 Door Key''\n| Joey\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| [[The Young Americans (film)|''The Young Americans'']]\n| Edward Foster\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Marar\u00eda]]''\n| Bertrand\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2000\n| ''[[Beautiful Creatures (2000 film)|Beautiful Creatures]]''\n| Tony\n|\n|-\n| [[Paranoid (2000 thriller film)|''Paranoid'']]\n| Stan\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2001\n| ''[[Lara Croft: Tomb Raider]]''\n| Manfred Powell\n| \n|-\n| [[Gabriel and Me|''Gabriel & Me'']]\n| Dad\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2002\n| [[Darkness (2002 film)|''Darkness'']]\n| Mark\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Soul Keeper]]''\n| [[Carl Gustav Jung|Dr. Carl Gustav Jung]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2003\n| ''[[Song for a Raggy Boy]]''\n| Brother John\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Spy Sorge]]''\n| [[Richard Sorge]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Resident Evil: Apocalypse]]''\n| Dr. Alexander Isaacs\n|\n|-\n| rowsp